  <div class="mb-4">
    <a onClick="toggleHelpOn()">
      <div id="help-btn" class="rounded-md bg-slate-300 text-slate-500 text-sm p-2">Instructions</div>
    </a>
    <a onClick="toggleHelpOff()">
      <div id="help" class="hidden">
        <div class="bg-slate-300 text-slate-500 text-sm p-2 rounded-t-md">Instructions</div>
        <div class="text-sm border border-slate-300 rounded-b-md p-4 text-left font-mono space-y-5">
          <p>
            You can compose your recipes using traditional Cooklang by surrounding ingredients using @ingredient{} symbols.  If you want to specify a quantity, put it inside the curly braces with a percent sign (%) separating the number and the unit - e.g., @chicken{5%pieces}.
          </p>

          <p>
            Alternatively, you can use the WYSIWYG editor.  First, type the recipe without any special markup.  Then, highlight the ingredients in your recipe.  A pop-up will appear to let you mark it as an ingredient.  After you've highlighted and marked all the ingredients, open up the Ingredient section and specify quantity (no percent sign needed).
          </p>

          <p>
            It's not recommended to use both cooklang-markup AND the WYSIWYG at the same time.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </a>
  </div>


<script type="text/javascript">
function toggleHelpOn() {
  document.getElementById('help-btn').classList.add('hidden');
  document.getElementById('help').classList.remove('hidden');
}

function toggleHelpOff() {
  document.getElementById('help-btn').classList.remove('hidden');
  document.getElementById('help').classList.add('hidden');
}
</script>